The world born of September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the 9/11 terrorist attacks in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four civil aircraft, launched two of the aircraft at the World Trade Center towers in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and then led to the crash of a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, many of whom believed it was the White House or another American government building in Washington, DC.
All the hijackers were from the Middle East, and 15 from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized, and led operation by Al-Qaïda (the 'base'), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children were mourned, and more than 6,000 were wounded.
Most were Americans, although citizens from over a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that the 9/11 events would usher in an era defined by global terrorism.
In fact, other terrorist attacks by Al-Qaeda followed, including several explosions on Madrid trains in March 2004, then the attack on public transportation in London in July 2005.
The terrorists who pledged allegiance to the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and instigated a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to hit pedestrians).
For this reason, neither the United States nor any of its allies have ever suffered an attack of comparable scope to those of September 11 – which are incommensurable.
It is therefore necessary to ask: Beyond immediate losses, what difference did September 11 make?
Has history changed and, if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why the terrorists were not able to perpetrate other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaïda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have put in place procedures for control making it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and aircraft.
The states have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the rare domains in which states often in disagreement are eager and willing to work together to a significant degree.
There is also now a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians, for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments should not be able to distinguish between terrorists and those who provide them with sanctuary and support.
Those days are over where individuals and groups ready to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters.
It is not a matter of claiming that terrorism has stopped from reaping dozens of thousands of lives every year.
However, almost all attacks occur in the Middle East, in Africa, and in South Asia as part of current conflicts (mainly in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks, of the 9/11 type, against major powers.
Terrorism is becoming more localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaeda, for example, survived the elimination of Ben Laden by U.S. special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the 9/11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism continues, without the problem being resolved on the horizon.
The possibility of a new September 11 cannot be ruled out either, although the American government has recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country existed on the domestic level.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army formulated after its failed assassination attempt of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today, we didn't have luck, but remember that we just need to have luck once.
You will always need it."
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists will get their hands on nuclear material, or will be able to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, at which point terrorism could determine the era.
For now, this is not the case.
The 11 September marked a historic turning point, with a profound impact on US foreign policy over the past 20 years.
Although the attacks did not lead to a global era of terrorism, they did indeed give rise to the famous global war on terror, with major consequences in the behavior of the United States around the world, America's image in the eyes of the world, and the way many Americans have come to consider their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Shortly after the 11 September attacks, the United States offered the Taliban, who controlled the Afghan government at the time, a choice: hand over the Al-Qaeda leaders who were on the verge of leaving the country and responsible for organizing the 11 September attacks, or risk their reign.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaïda leaders, U.S. intelligence and military collaborated with an unstructured Afghan tribal confederation called the Northern Alliance to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
However, this control was never total, nor uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaïda fled to neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually regrouped and resumed military operations against the government that had replaced them.
On their part, the United States did not work sufficiently to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of a sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, America strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, becoming essentially a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the US intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of the operations amounts to over $2,000 billion, for more than 2,300 American lives lost, and several tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The American presence deprived the Afghan government of a great deal of its legitimacy, and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persistent than America, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict doomed to end in an undefined stalemate.
World War on terror also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily if September 11 had not occurred.
The attacks certainly strengthened his tendency to want to tell the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had formulated during the Vietnam War, a "powerless and pitiful giant".
This led some members of the administration (first and foremost, Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of seeing terrorists seize weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (which was not the case in the end) according to most of the protagonists.
Others aimed to spread democracy in Iraq, and then throughout the entire Middle East, considering that this approach was not only achievable but would also make the region much less susceptible to producing terrorists and supporting them.
Triggered in March 2003, the war in Iraq did not unfold as had been wished or foreseen by the Bush administration, as well as by the many members of Congress (including Joe Biden, then senator) and world leaders who had approved it.
The United States were not prepared for the essential events that were to come.
The military victories won in the first place certainly allowed the government to be chased, but quickly gave way to widespread agitation as well as a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army, and to exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs, worsened a situation that was already chaotic.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, demonstrated the limits of what military force can accomplish at a reasonable cost and within reasonable timeframes.
In the end, the United States has been forced to strengthen its military presence, to bring it to nearly 170,000 soldiers, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability has been achieved, but at a considerable price.
The United States has spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but at a much heavier human cost: more than 4,000 American soldiers killed, a significantly larger number of wounded, and an exploding rate of suicide among American military personnel (from Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total excludes, in addition, deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for which the estimates vary widely, but the number certainly rises to several hundred thousand.
The war in Iraq has also weakened the United States in other respects.
No evidence has ever demonstrated Iraq's implication in the 9/11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for a military intervention without UN approval – aiming to eliminate Saddam's WMDs – proved to be based on no real grounds.
The images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners further tarnished the country's reputation.
Furthermore, an Iraq at war with itself became synonymous with an emerging Iran as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if considering Israel).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also turned out to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States became intensely involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking great powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted in favor of the United States, both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia, as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The war on global terrorism could not provide and did not provide the United States with a compass in their foreign policy approach to a renewed rivalry between great powers.
The wars that followed September 11 also had significant domestic consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War with a historically unparalleled preponderant power, and harmed the national unity that had emerged in the immediate aftermath of the attacks.
In addition, the costs and failures associated with these wars have also fueled opposition to a major and lasting global role for the United States, giving rise to a new isolationist trend.
Similarly, this warlike propensity, associated with the 2007-2009 global financial crisis and its economic repercussions, has severely impacted the Americans' trust in the elite, thus stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to the arrival of power of Donald Trump.
Today's America is more divided than ever on the domestic front, and less willing to lead this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which largely benefited the Americans as well as many others in general.
With hindsight, we can now consider September 11 as a precursor sign of what was to come: less the globalization of terrorism than the fears of globalization.
The attacks sent the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global era.
Nothing remains local for long anymore, whether it is terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis that originated from poor American financial management.
Currently, we are all faced with a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its appearance in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that are devastating many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself a cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable amounts of greenhouse gas heat trappers into the atmosphere.
The era begun by recent events marks the end of a cycle, marking the 20th anniversary of US intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly driven out of power; over the past few weeks, they have just as easily regained it.
It's too early to know if the Taliban will renew their old habits by becoming once again a haven for terrorism, and if terrorists around the world will boast of their victory over America and its allies.
We know, on the other hand, that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that, for its part, already determines it.
